licationst paulo vitor jordão da gama silva · federal rural university of rio de janeirond antônio carlos figueiredo pinto · pontifícia universidade católica do rio de janeirord marcelo klotzle · pontifícia universidade católica do rio de janeiroabstractthis article analyses the pricing using autocall mechanisms of a coupon barrier note issue based on adrs of brazils biggest mining and metals company vale sa vale the numerical method used was based on a modification of the trinomial tree model with autocall barrier and knockin conditions and which was modified to calculate present value this model was shown to be practical and agile for processing the database and handling considerably volatile scenarios and was also validated by the products actual behaviour revealing that the product was not financially attractive for maintaining an autocall operation strategy achieve a gain with the product maturing in the short term and switch to similar products the aim of this article is to show a new pricing method involving autocall structured products with functioning typologies similar to those of the issue analysed in the present studydiscover the worlds research million members million publicationsk research projectsjoin for free figures int j financial markets and derivatives vol  no    copyright   inderscience enterprises ltd autocall structured products a case study of vale sa paulo vitor jordão da gama silva antonio carlos figueiredo pinto and marcelo cabus klotzle department of administration ima institute of management and administration pontifical catholic university of rio de janeiro pucrj rua marquês de são vicente  gávea – rio de janeiro rj –  –  brazil email rjdagamaigcombr email figueiredoiagpucriobr email klotzleiagpucriobr corresponding author abstract this article analyses the pricing using autocall mechanisms of a coupon barrier note issue based on adrs of brazil’s biggest mining and metals company vale sa vale the numerical method used was based on a modification of the trinomial tree model with autocall barrier and knockin conditions and which was modified to calculate present value this model was shown to be practical and agile for processing the database and handling considerably volatile scenarios and was also validated by the product’s actual behaviour revealing that the product was not financially attractive for maintaining an autocall operation strategy achieve a gain with the product maturing in the short term and switch to similar products the aim of this article is to show a new pricing method involving autocall structured products with functioning typologies similar to those of the issue analysed in the present study keywords financial derivatives structured products autocall vale sa vale modified trinomial tree finite difference method reference to this paper should be made as follows da gama silva pvj figueiredo pinto ac and klotzle mc  ‘autocall structured products a case study of vale sa’ int j financial markets and derivatives vol  no  pp– biographical notes paulo vitor jordão da gama silva obtained a degree in business administration from the pontifical catholic university of rio de janeiro  he has a master’s in business administration with an emphasis on finance at the same university  antônio carlos figueiredo pinto obtained a degree in administration from the rio de janeiro state university  he has a phd in economics from the epge of the getulio vargas foundation – rj  he is currently a professor at the pontifical catholic university of rio de janeiro he has published various articles in the field of administration with an emphasis on derivatives financial markets and portfolio management he has published books and articles in brazil and abroad  pvj da gama silva et al marcelo cabus klotzle holds a degree in administration – university of bayreuth  a master’s degree in administration – universityof bayreuth  and a phd in economics – catholic university of eichstätt  he obtained a postdoctoral degree in behavioral finance from mcmaster university  he is currently a professor at the pontifical catholic university of rio de janeiro he has a wide experience in the administration and economics areas with an emphasis on financial administration capital markets and international economics and finance and is mainly engaged with the following themes corporate governance behavioural finance capital markets econometrics international finance and the international economy he has published books and articles in brazil and abroad  introduction in recent years retail and high net income investors all over the world have been seeking new investment opportunities that offer attractive returns and therefore considering products that differ from traditional investments although not necessarily seeking full principal protection thus products that enhance these yields such as autocall products have become increasingly popular with investors according to deng et al  there has been a sharp increase in their use with  annual growth recorded between  and  more than  autocall products were issued during the first six months of  according to baule et al  bergstresser  deng et al  and henderson and pearson  one of the reasons for this increase in autocall products is the ease with which they can be indexed to the products acting essentially as a marketlinked investment that faces ‘forced redemption’ before the scheduled maturity date if certain predetermined market conditions are achieved drawing on georgieva’s  considerations regarding structured products and adapting these ideas to autocall dynamics one may add a few more benefits of using this tool such as using it to hedge at a minimum or maximum level when hedging instruments are not available in the shortterm market take on risk judiciously in order to obtain higher returns diversify in order to manage risk in the case of autocall with more than one asset avoid problems with potential market impact due to significant changes in asset allocation amongst others an autocall event occurs on predetermined dates which can occur at annual quarterly intervals etc specific for each type of product that can mature on the autocall date the latter may be continuous or discrete as shown in figure a and b in the case of a continuous autocall date the product can only be autocalled when it attains the barrier during its whole duration whereas in the discrete case there are certain ‘autocall dates’ on which the product may or may not face ‘forced redemption’ depending on its position in relation to the barrier level the latter is characteristic of the vale sa product analysed with its predetermined dates the underlying reference index s can be linked to the price of stocks a basket of stocks or funds amongst others such that if it reaches price level ‘c’ the company exercises the option to purchase the product which is then automatically redeemed with the investor receiving the predetermined coupon initially agreed upon by contract along with the principal invested autocall structured products  figure  autocall in continuous and discrete periods a continuous autocall b discrete autocall see online version for colours a b source citifirst – informações sobre termos e condições in figure  examples the products were subject to autocall before the maturity date most autocall products have a protection feature so that if the autocall trigger has not occurred before the scheduled maturity date the capital is fully protected and the investor receives all interest due provided the price is greater than or equal to the barrier level however if s is below this level investors will be fully exposed to downside of the market and may suffer heavy losses thus is important to necessary to understand that the autocall product necessarily includes a put option on the maturity date it is also interesting to observe that the ‘small’ period of time that has elapsed since its creation has seen the development of several variations of the original autocall model such as performance autocall crescendo autocall escalator autocall bonus autocall and the premium express with all of them influenced by characteristic instruments used to calculate payments on coupon dates this article is divided into six sections after this introduction section  presents the model developed to analyse the pricing of the autocall product issued by vale sa as well as a review of the literature aimed at gaining a deeper knowledge of autocall mechanisms the third provides a detailed explanation of the study’s title section  presents the methodology used and important data the section  shows the empirical results obtained and section  presents the study’s conclusions  theoretical references this section performs an indepth analysis of themes related to the models used for the pricing of autocall structured products which are the trinomial tree and finite difference models it will also focus on autocall theory itself encompassing the most common types and their forms of payment  trinomial tree model the trinomial tree was introduced for the first time by boyle  and explained in hull  and haug  it is seen as constituting an extension of the binomial approach from cox et al  and is conceptually similar according to the trinomial  pvj da gama silva et al method the underlying stock is modelled as a recombination tree where the price has three possible paths at each node upwards downwards or stable for standard type options where the number of steps increases results converge rapidly and the binomial model is then preferred due to its simple implementation however in the case of exotic options the trinomial model or adaptations shows more stable and precise results independently of the size of the step according to the trinomial method the price of the underlying stock is modelled as a recombination tree where the price has three possible paths at each node upwards downwards and a stable or middle one these values are found by multiplying the value at the current node by the appropriate factor where tueσ××δ  tde uσ−× ×δ  m  u  price x’ s multiplicative additive increase factor d  price x’s multiplicative additive decrease factor m  price x’s multiplicative stability factor figure  illustrates the dynamics of stock prices in the trinomial tree using n   steps for the time figure  demonstration of the trinomial model source rouah andvainberg  autocall structured products  in order to contain all possible price movements in a trinomial tree with n steps one needs a matrix with n   lines and n  columns corresponding to a size  ×  matrix the increase decrease and stability probabilities are represented in this order by the following formulas ttrqtteepueeσσσδδ−×−×δδ×−×⎛⎞−⎜⎟⎜⎟−⎝⎠  ttrqtteepdeeσσσδδ×−×δδ×−×⎛⎞−⎜⎟⎜⎟−⎝⎠  pm pu pd−   where δ t is the period of time ơ is the volatility adopted r is the rate of interest paid q represents dividend payments which in this case would is zero and pu and pd are unconditionally positive the modification of the tree for the pricing of structured products with complex variables is introduced for the first time in this study and will be detailed later in the methodology as a model which seeks to simply the calculation by adopting a processing dynamic that is low in terms of computational capacity it should be noted that this model was chosen because according to anderson et al  it is clear that implicit methods require additional computation skills and their implementation can be much more difficult implicit methods are used in problems where the use of an explicit method would require impracticably small steps to ensure limited errors to attain the precision sought after in such problems much less computational time is necessary than when using an implicit method they are usually unconditionally stable and it is thus possible to use greater values in the steps so that a solution may be found more quickly however the computational cost also increases considerably which in turn increases the need for extensive database processing a modelling that is similar to the trinomial model can be found in the explicit finite difference method which will be described below  the finite difference model according to collatz  the finite difference model is a method for solving differential equations that is based on derivate approximation by finite differences the formulas for finite differences can be obtained by developing taylor series – see for example ames  roache  and lapidus and piner  the derived finite difference operator can be obtained from the taylor series for the function    xhxxhoh  ∫∫∫ thus the derivative can be written as a difference plus an error term  pvj da gama silva et al  xh xxohh−∫∫∫ ignoring the error term one obtains the finite difference operator for the first derivative f defined as  xhxdx h−∫∫∫  according to vista  regarding precision and order the error in the solution of a method is defined as the difference between its approximation and the exact analytical solution the two sources of error in finite difference methods are the rounding error which is the loss of precision due to computational rounding of decimal amounts – which can also occur in the trinomial model jeopardising the results of very sensitive models and the truncation error which is the residual that results when the exact solution of the dependent variable in the discretised equation of the mathematical model is substituted in order to use a finite difference method to try to solve or usually obtain an approximate solution of a problem one should first discretise the domination problem this is usually performed by dividing the domination into a uniform grid as can be seen in figure  figure  discretisation of a function on a grid see online version for colours source kaw and kalu  note that this means that finite difference methods produce discrete sets of numerical approximations for the derivative temporally in steps the most common examples of this method are expressed in the form of ordinary differential equations and in the heat equation in the approach of the model used by deng et al  for the pricing of autocall products the authors use an explicit calculation of finite differences and partial differential equations pde with the blackscholes formula as presented by zvan et al  which discusses the pde methodology for the pricing of barrier options it is also worth mentioning that the monte carlo model is another option of numerical method for the valuation of structured products autocall structured products   autocall according to fries and joshi  and georgieva  the use of autocall structure products has become common in recent years also because they act similarly to a rational investor who has a broad view of the underlying asset according to deng et al  the fact that most structured products were of longer term around five years or more was regarded as a negative factor by many investors throughout the world an interesting way of enhancing the reduction of an investment’s duration was discovered with the use of autocall products which according to alexander and sheedy  essentially function like a european barrier option in which if at a predetermined future date the market is above a defined trigger level the structure will be automatically revoked with investors receiving their principal along with a specified return the eightyear period since the first autocall product was produced in  has seen a series of innovations that have refined the original model which according to citifirst  are • performance autocall in which the autocall coupon is not fixed at a specific level but pays the greater of x and the actual underlying performance in the case of an autocall event • crescendo autocall in which the autocall event depends on two underlyings being above the autocall barrier and besides this there is an additional condition in which the second underlying provides additional financing for higher autocall coupons • escalator autocall in which the autocall barrier decreases each year – increasing the likelihood of an autocall event and reducing the probability of capital at risk • bonus plus autocall in which besides the autocall coupon received at automatic maturity investors receive a bonus coupon in this case the earlier in the life of the product autocall occurs the better so that the effective per annum coupon is high in early years compared with a standard autocall note thus reducing the value of coupon payments towards maturity • premium express in which the autocall barrier is below  of the initial strike level aiming to provide a high autocall probability with full capital protection bouzoubaa and osseiran  perform a descriptive analysis of the main autocall structures considering payments performance and the dispersion effect itself also considering hypothetical explanatory scenarios in order to better understand the analyses that follow below  unique assets subject to autocall  payments description considering a product with autocall based in one single asset s the structure pays a coupon that depends basically on the underlying achieving trigger levels h and b and whose payments are defined on each observation date ti i  n as follows  pvj da gama silva et al  ti tjret b max j  i  retcoupon ti invst c  h⎡⎤⎡ ⎤≥……− ⎢⎥⎣⎦⎣⎦×× ×  where invst is the initial investment c is the predetermined coupon and retti  sti  s is the return during period ti at the initial strike level s if a wrapper strategy is applied to the note the investor will receive  of the invst in this case however the payment is not fixed the invst can be redeemed on any observation date not necessarily at the end of the product’s life      ti tjret hmax j i ret hredemption ti invst⎡⎤⎡ ⎤≥……− ⎢⎥⎣⎦⎣⎦× ×  in the case of the payment described above it is important to observe that the investor does not receive an additional payment if h is achieved on one of the observation dates so a product is considered to have been autocalled if its lifecycle is interrupted when barrier h is achieved by the underlying on a specific observation date the autocall structure itself does not have a fixed lifecycle until maturity maturity in fact is the maximum amount of time that a product manages to remain active the autocall trigger h is a predetermined level above which the autocall structure terminates and the investor receives the invst invested trigger i can be fixed during the life of the product or may vary in some cases the trigger may also increase or decrease over time the coupon trigger b also known as the coupon level is a predetermined level above which the investor receives a periodic coupon in other words if the underlying observation level is greater than the coupon trigger a coupon based on the invst is paid to the investor the autocall and coupon triggers of some structures involving autocall are equal and are known as autocall products with knockout coupons however when the coupon is paid the product is autocalled at the same time provided the autocall trigger has been attained thus this structure pays a single coupon on an observation date during the whole life of the product in cases in which the coupon level is different from the autocall trigger the products are known as autocall products with knockin coupons  payment mechanisms this section explains the various payment mechanisms through the simulation of scenarios shown in tables  and  accompanied by figures  and  with a specific case to better understand the autocall structure consider a retail investor in an investment bank who invests us  in an autocall structured product based on the cac  index with a threeyear duration table  payment scenarios for a structured product with autocall involving the cac index scenario  scenario  scenario  coupon in the end of the year     coupon in the end of the year     coupon in the end of the year     source bouzoubaa and osseiran  p autocall struct