that is concerned with being agile enough to process large databases in order to maintain the data accuracy necessary to ensure the adequate functioning of these structured products enables investors to assess whether the product’s return according to its historic volatility is over or underestimated therefore based on the information collected or scenarios developed investors will be able to undertake their operations which may be hedging arbitrage or speculative autocall structured products  operations – depending on the type of product thus it is necessary to calibrate models to the reality of the market in which they will be used and to product typology references alexander c and sheedy e  the professional risk managers guide to financial instruments st ed prmia new york ames wf  numerical methods for partial differential equation nd ed academic press new york anderson d pletcher r and tannehill jc  computational fluid mechanics and heat transfer nd ed taylor  francis philadelphia baule r entrop o and wilkens m  ‘credit risk and bank margins in structured financial products evidence from the german secondary market for discount certificates’ journal of futures markets vol  no  pp– bergstresser bd  the retail market for structured notes insurance patterns and performance working paper  harvard business school harvard university boston bloomberg online httpwwwbloombergcom accessed  february  bouzoubaa m and osseiran a  exotic options and hybrids a guide to structuring pricing and trading st ed john wiley  sons west sussex uk boyle p  ‘option valuation using a threejump process’ international options journal vol  no  pp– citifirst  designation of citigroup’s family of investment strategies  online httpswwwcitifirstcomptdefaultaspxforcept accessed  august  collatz l  the numerical treatment of differential equations rd ed springerverlag berlin cox j ross s and rubinstein m  ‘option pricing a simplified approach’ journal of financial economics vol  no  pp– da silva l